{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PGti3cdaKqvV8nXwg33fB6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01UsbXq3NCgRM5UTeZQ9tYwa","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"grep -n \"#leanfile\" /home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ /home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/e88-architecture.typ 2>/dev/null | head -100","description":"Find all leanfile references in both typ files"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":135,"cache_read_input_tokens":27270,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":135},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"23a5d44b-efaf-4468-b1ae-0b067e647cf0","uuid":"97bcb183-babb-4794-ba86-fd8d1296af39"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UsbXq3NCgRM5UTeZQ9tYwa","type":"tool_result","content":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:18:  In any linear recurrence with contraction factor $|alpha| < 1$, state decays exponentially: $|h_T| = O(alpha^T |h_0|)$. Information from timestep $0$ is attenuated by factor $alpha^T$ at timestep $T$.#leanfile(\"LinearCapacity.lean:72\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:24:  A linear recurrence cannot store a binary fact (e.g., \"flag was set\") indefinitely. Either the state decays to zero ($|alpha| < 1$) or it explodes ($|alpha| > 1$). There is no stable retention.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:360\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:35:  where $S in RR^(d times d)$ is matrix state, $alpha in (0, 2)$ is the retention coefficient, $delta$ is input scaling, and $v_t k_t^top$ is the rank-1 outer product update from current input.#leanfile(\"E88Definition.lean:127\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:59:  Each update $v_t k_t^top$ is rank-1, contributing $2d$ degrees of freedom. After $T$ timesteps with linearly independent inputs, the cumulative information is $T times 2d$ values. The tanh nonlinearity mixes these across all $d^2$ matrix entries. For $T >= d$, the state can achieve full rank $d$, utilizing the full $d^2$-dimensional state space.#leanfile(\"E88RankAccumulation.lean:45\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:62:This contrasts sharply with linear matrix recurrences, where rank growth is bounded by $min(T, d)$ regardless of sequence length.#leanfile(\"E88RankAccumulation.lean:120\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:71:  As $|tanh(x)| -> 1$, the derivative $tanh'(x) -> 0$. Near saturation, perturbations have diminishing effect.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:87\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:77:  - When $alpha > 1$: Zero becomes unstable. Two new stable fixed points emerge at $plus.minus S^*$ where $S^* = tanh(alpha S^*)$.#leanfile(\"AttentionPersistence.lean:212\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:91:  For $alpha in (0.9, 1.1)$ and small input scaling $|delta| < 0.1$: once $|S_(i j)| > 0.9$, subsequent updates with bounded inputs maintain $|S_(i j)| > 0.85$. The latched state persists.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:320\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:97:  In a linear recurrence $S_t = alpha S_(t-1)$ with $|alpha| < 1$: $|S_T| = |alpha|^T |S_0| -> 0$ exponentially. No stable non-zero state exists.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:360\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:109:  With appropriate parameters ($alpha = 1$, $delta = 2$ in a simplified 1D case): input 0 preserves the sign of $S$; input 1 flips the sign. The sign encodes running parity $x_1 xor x_2 xor dots xor x_t$.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:720\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:117:  Accumulated positive signal drives $S$ toward $+1$. Accumulated negative signal drives toward $-1$. The transition sharpens as accumulation grows, approaching a hard threshold.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:424\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:120:Linear-temporal models cannot compute threshold functions because linear functions are continuous and threshold functions are discontinuous.#leanfile(\"LinearLimitations.lean:107\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:125:  For small $n <= 8$, E88 can maintain $n$ distinct stable states, counting inputs modulo $n$. The tanh creates $n$ attractors at approximately $-1 + 2i/(n-1)$ for $i = 0, dots, n-1$.#leanfile(\"E88Definition.lean:276\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:149:The entries marked \"provably impossible\" are not empirical observations—they are mathematical facts verified in Lean. The capacity separation ($d^2 > d$ for $d >= 2$) and retrieval separation are proven in `E1HDefinition.lean` and `E88ExceedsE1HCapacity.lean`; the full three-way hierarchy is assembled in `ExpressivityHierarchy.lean`.#leanfile(\"ExpressivityHierarchy.lean:267\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:154:  An $H$-head E88 is equivalent to $H$ independent state machines. Head $h_1$'s state depends only on its own parameters $(alpha_(h_1), delta_(h_1), K_(h_1), V_(h_1))$ and the input sequence—not on other heads' parameters or states.#leanfile(\"E88Definition.lean:389\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:169:  Once a head enters an alert state, it remains alert across subsequent timesteps with bounded inputs. The saturated element's magnitude remains above threshold.#leanfile(\"E88Definition.lean:433\")","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"23a5d44b-efaf-4468-b1ae-0b067e647cf0","uuid":"059b295c-16c9-47fc-915f-e5527208d416","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:18:  In any linear recurrence with contraction factor $|alpha| < 1$, state decays exponentially: $|h_T| = O(alpha^T |h_0|)$. Information from timestep $0$ is attenuated by factor $alpha^T$ at timestep $T$.#leanfile(\"LinearCapacity.lean:72\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:24:  A linear recurrence cannot store a binary fact (e.g., \"flag was set\") indefinitely. Either the state decays to zero ($|alpha| < 1$) or it explodes ($|alpha| > 1$). There is no stable retention.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:360\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:35:  where $S in RR^(d times d)$ is matrix state, $alpha in (0, 2)$ is the retention coefficient, $delta$ is input scaling, and $v_t k_t^top$ is the rank-1 outer product update from current input.#leanfile(\"E88Definition.lean:127\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:59:  Each update $v_t k_t^top$ is rank-1, contributing $2d$ degrees of freedom. After $T$ timesteps with linearly independent inputs, the cumulative information is $T times 2d$ values. The tanh nonlinearity mixes these across all $d^2$ matrix entries. For $T >= d$, the state can achieve full rank $d$, utilizing the full $d^2$-dimensional state space.#leanfile(\"E88RankAccumulation.lean:45\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:62:This contrasts sharply with linear matrix recurrences, where rank growth is bounded by $min(T, d)$ regardless of sequence length.#leanfile(\"E88RankAccumulation.lean:120\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:71:  As $|tanh(x)| -> 1$, the derivative $tanh'(x) -> 0$. Near saturation, perturbations have diminishing effect.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:87\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:77:  - When $alpha > 1$: Zero becomes unstable. Two new stable fixed points emerge at $plus.minus S^*$ where $S^* = tanh(alpha S^*)$.#leanfile(\"AttentionPersistence.lean:212\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:91:  For $alpha in (0.9, 1.1)$ and small input scaling $|delta| < 0.1$: once $|S_(i j)| > 0.9$, subsequent updates with bounded inputs maintain $|S_(i j)| > 0.85$. The latched state persists.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:320\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:97:  In a linear recurrence $S_t = alpha S_(t-1)$ with $|alpha| < 1$: $|S_T| = |alpha|^T |S_0| -> 0$ exponentially. No stable non-zero state exists.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:360\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:109:  With appropriate parameters ($alpha = 1$, $delta = 2$ in a simplified 1D case): input 0 preserves the sign of $S$; input 1 flips the sign. The sign encodes running parity $x_1 xor x_2 xor dots xor x_t$.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:720\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:117:  Accumulated positive signal drives $S$ toward $+1$. Accumulated negative signal drives toward $-1$. The transition sharpens as accumulation grows, approaching a hard threshold.#leanfile(\"TanhSaturation.lean:424\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:120:Linear-temporal models cannot compute threshold functions because linear functions are continuous and threshold functions are discontinuous.#leanfile(\"LinearLimitations.lean:107\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:125:  For small $n <= 8$, E88 can maintain $n$ distinct stable states, counting inputs modulo $n$. The tanh creates $n$ attractors at approximately $-1 + 2i/(n-1)$ for $i = 0, dots, n-1$.#leanfile(\"E88Definition.lean:276\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:149:The entries marked \"provably impossible\" are not empirical observations—they are mathematical facts verified in Lean. The capacity separation ($d^2 > d$ for $d >= 2$) and retrieval separation are proven in `E1HDefinition.lean` and `E88ExceedsE1HCapacity.lean`; the full three-way hierarchy is assembled in `ExpressivityHierarchy.lean`.#leanfile(\"ExpressivityHierarchy.lean:267\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:154:  An $H$-head E88 is equivalent to $H$ independent state machines. Head $h_1$'s state depends only on its own parameters $(alpha_(h_1), delta_(h_1), K_(h_1), V_(h_1))$ and the input sequence—not on other heads' parameters or states.#leanfile(\"E88Definition.lean:389\")\n/home/erikg/elman-proofs/docs/expressivity/04-e88.typ:169:  Once a head enters an alert state, it remains alert across subsequent timesteps with bounded inputs. The saturated element's magnitude remains above threshold.#leanfile(\"E88Definition.lean:433\")","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
