{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JJzo7F9WKV4ZdkBpwue6p3","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\n     3→Released under Apache 2.0 license.\n     4→Authors: Elman Project Contributors\n     5→-/\n     6→import Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\n     7→import Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.Trace\n     8→import Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\n     9→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Pow.Real\n    10→import Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Dimension.Finrank\n    11→\n    12→/-!\n    13→# Linear State Capacity Bounds\n    14→\n    15→This file proves that d-dimensional linear RNN state carries at most O(d) bits\n    16→of information about the input history.\n    17→\n    18→## Main Results\n    19→\n    20→* `linear_state_is_sum`: State at time T is a sum of weighted inputs\n    21→* `output_determined_by_state`: Output depends only on current state\n    22→* `same_state_same_future`: Same state → same future outputs\n    23→\n    24→## Key Insight\n    25→\n    26→Linear RNNs cannot \"compute\" on their state - they can only linearly combine past inputs.\n    27→This fundamentally limits what patterns they can detect, unlike nonlinear RNNs which can\n    28→implement arbitrary computations on the hidden state.\n    29→\n    30→The state h_T = Σ_{t=0}^{T-1} A^{T-1-t} B x_t is just a weighted sum of inputs,\n    31→where the weights are determined by powers of A. This means:\n    32→1. At most n linearly independent \"features\" can be extracted from any input sequence\n    33→2. Two input sequences that produce the same state are indistinguishable for all future outputs\n    34→\n    35→-/\n    36→\n    37→namespace Expressivity\n    38→\n    39→open Matrix Finset BigOperators\n    40→\n    41→variable {n m k : ℕ}\n    42→\n    43→/-! ## Linear RNN State Evolution -/\n    44→\n    45→/-- Single step of linear RNN: h' = A h + B x -/\n    46→def linearStep (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ) (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ)\n    47→    (h : Fin n → ℝ) (x : Fin m → ℝ) : Fin n → ℝ :=\n    48→  A.mulVec h + B.mulVec x\n    49→\n    50→/-- State after T steps starting from h₀, given input sequence.\n    51→    Uses recursion: h_{t+1} = A h_t + B x_t -/\n    52→def stateAfterT (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ) (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ)\n    53→    (h₀ : Fin n → ℝ) : (T : ℕ) → (Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) → (Fin n → ℝ)\n    54→  | 0, _ => h₀\n    55→  | T' + 1, inputs =>\n    56→    linearStep A B (stateAfterT A B h₀ T' (fun i => inputs i.castSucc)) (inputs (Fin.last T'))\n    57→\n    58→/-- State after T steps starting from zero initial state -/\n    59→def stateFromZero (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ) (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ)\n    60→    (T : ℕ) (inputs : Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) : Fin n → ℝ :=\n    61→  stateAfterT A B 0 T inputs\n    62→\n    63→/-! ## State is Linear Combination of Inputs -/\n    64→\n    65→/-- The contribution of input at time t to state at time T is A^{T-1-t} * B * x_t -/\n    66→def inputContribution (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ) (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ)\n    67→    (T : ℕ) (t : Fin T) (x : Fin m → ℝ) : Fin n → ℝ :=\n    68→  (A ^ (T - 1 - t.val)).mulVec (B.mulVec x)\n    69→\n    70→/-- State at time T starting from zero is the sum of contributions from all inputs.\n    71→    h_T = Σ_{t=0}^{T-1} A^{T-1-t} B x_t -/\n    72→theorem linear_state_is_sum (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ) (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ)\n    73→    (T : ℕ) (inputs : Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) :\n    74→    stateFromZero A B T inputs = ∑ t : Fin T, inputContribution A B T t (inputs t) := by\n    75→  induction T with\n    76→  | zero =>\n    77→    simp only [stateFromZero, stateAfterT, Finset.univ_eq_empty, sum_empty]\n    78→  | succ T' ih =>\n    79→    simp only [stateFromZero, stateAfterT, linearStep]\n    80→    -- Apply IH: state(T') = Σ t : Fin T', A^(T'-1-t) B x_{t.castSucc}\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"23a5d44b-efaf-4468-b1ae-0b067e647cf0","uuid":"f8365c77-00b1-4442-9780-1c0fc4eb0850","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/LinearCapacity.lean","content":"/-\nCopyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\nReleased under Apache 2.0 license.\nAuthors: Elman Project Contributors\n-/\nimport Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\nimport Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.Trace\nimport Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Pow.Real\nimport Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Dimension.Finrank\n\n/-!\n# Linear State Capacity Bounds\n\nThis file proves that d-dimensional linear RNN state carries at most O(d) bits\nof information about the input history.\n\n## Main Results\n\n* `linear_state_is_sum`: State at time T is a sum of weighted inputs\n* `output_determined_by_state`: Output depends only on current state\n* `same_state_same_future`: Same state → same future outputs\n\n## Key Insight\n\nLinear RNNs cannot \"compute\" on their state - they can only linearly combine past inputs.\nThis fundamentally limits what patterns they can detect, unlike nonlinear RNNs which can\nimplement arbitrary computations on the hidden state.\n\nThe state h_T = Σ_{t=0}^{T-1} A^{T-1-t} B x_t is just a weighted sum of inputs,\nwhere the weights are determined by powers of A. This means:\n1. At most n linearly independent \"features\" can be extracted from any input sequence\n2. Two input sequences that produce the same state are indistinguishable for all future outputs\n\n-/\n\nnamespace Expressivity\n\nopen Matrix Finset BigOperators\n\nvariable {n m k : ℕ}\n\n/-! ## Linear RNN State Evolution -/\n\n/-- Single step of linear RNN: h' = A h + B x -/\ndef linearStep (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ) (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ)\n    (h : Fin n → ℝ) (x : Fin m → ℝ) : Fin n → ℝ :=\n  A.mulVec h + B.mulVec x\n\n/-- State after T steps starting from h₀, given input sequence.\n    Uses recursion: h_{t+1} = A h_t + B x_t -/\ndef stateAfterT (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ) (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ)\n    (h₀ : Fin n → ℝ) : (T : ℕ) → (Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) → (Fin n → ℝ)\n  | 0, _ => h₀\n  | T' + 1, inputs =>\n    linearStep A B (stateAfterT A B h₀ T' (fun i => inputs i.castSucc)) (inputs (Fin.last T'))\n\n/-- State after T steps starting from zero initial state -/\ndef stateFromZero (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ) (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ)\n    (T : ℕ) (inputs : Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) : Fin n → ℝ :=\n  stateAfterT A B 0 T inputs\n\n/-! ## State is Linear Combination of Inputs -/\n\n/-- The contribution of input at time t to state at time T is A^{T-1-t} * B * x_t -/\ndef inputContribution (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ) (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ)\n    (T : ℕ) (t : Fin T) (x : Fin m → ℝ) : Fin n → ℝ :=\n  (A ^ (T - 1 - t.val)).mulVec (B.mulVec x)\n\n/-- State at time T starting from zero is the sum of contributions from all inputs.\n    h_T = Σ_{t=0}^{T-1} A^{T-1-t} B x_t -/\ntheorem linear_state_is_sum (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ) (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ)\n    (T : ℕ) (inputs : Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) :\n    stateFromZero A B T inputs = ∑ t : Fin T, inputContribution A B T t (inputs t) := by\n  induction T with\n  | zero =>\n    simp only [stateFromZero, stateAfterT, Finset.univ_eq_empty, sum_empty]\n  | succ T' ih =>\n    simp only [stateFromZero, stateAfterT, linearStep]\n    -- Apply IH: state(T') = Σ t : Fin T', A^(T'-1-t) B x_{t.castSucc}","numLines":80,"startLine":1,"totalLines":255}}}
