{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TvLjr9MXemYVnEc3yDEStz","type":"tool_result","content":"1:/-\n22:/-!\n67:/-! ## Part 1: Tanh Saturation Properties -/\n69:/-- Tanh approaches ±1 as input magnitude grows. Already proven as tendsto_tanh_atTop. -/\n70:theorem tanh_saturates_to_one : Filter.Tendsto tanh Filter.atTop (nhds 1) :=\n73:/-- Tanh approaches -1 as input approaches -∞. -/\n74:theorem tanh_saturates_to_neg_one : Filter.Tendsto tanh Filter.atBot (nhds (-1)) := by\n85:/-- The derivative of tanh vanishes as |x| → ∞. This is the key saturation property.\n87:theorem tanh_derivative_vanishes (ε : ℝ) (hε : 0 < ε) :\n91:/-! ## Part 2: Fixed Point Analysis for Tanh Recurrence -/\n93:/-- A simple tanh recurrence: S_{t+1} = tanh(α·S_t + b) -/\n94:noncomputable def tanhRecurrence (α b : ℝ) (S : ℝ) : ℝ := tanh (α * S + b)\n96:/-- When |α| < 1, the tanh recurrence is a contraction on [-1, 1].\n98:theorem tanhRecurrence_is_contraction (α : ℝ) (_hα : |α| < 1) (b : ℝ) :\n114:/-- For |α| < 1, the tanh recurrence has a unique fixed point. -/\n115:theorem tanhRecurrence_unique_fixedpoint (α : ℝ) (hα_lt : |α| < 1) (_hα_pos : 0 < |α|) (b : ℝ) :\n158:/-- Near saturation (|S| close to 1), the state becomes \"latched\" because\n160:theorem near_saturation_low_gradient (α : ℝ) (_hα : |α| ≤ 1) (b S : ℝ)\n188:/-! ## Part 3: Binary Retention - Latching vs Decay -/\n190:/-- E88-style state update with tanh nonlinearity.\n192:noncomputable def e88StateUpdate (α : ℝ) (S k : ℝ) (δ : ℝ) : ℝ := tanh (α * S + δ * k)\n194:/-- Linear state update (Mamba2-style): S_{t+1} = α·S_t + B·x_t -/\n195:noncomputable def linearStateUpdate (α : ℝ) (S x : ℝ) (B : ℝ) : ℝ := α * S + B * x\n197:/-- A latched state in E88: once |S| is close to 1, it stays close to 1.\n204:theorem e88_latched_state_persists (α : ℝ) (hα : 0 < α) (hα_lt : α < 2) (hα_large : α > 9/10)\n337:/-- Linear state decays exponentially when |α| < 1 (stable case). -/\n338:theorem linear_state_decay (α : ℝ) (hα : |α| < 1) (S₀ : ℝ) :\n358:/-- The key difference: E88 can maintain a nonzero state indefinitely,\n360:theorem latching_vs_decay :\n411:/-! ## Part 4: Exact Counting with Tanh -/\n413:/-- A counting state: tracks count mod n using saturating dynamics.\n421:/-- E88 can implement a counter mod n for small n by using multiple heads\n424:theorem e88_can_count_mod (n : ℕ) (hn : 0 < n) :\n489:/-- Linear systems cannot count: they can only track weighted sums.\n498:theorem linear_cannot_count_exactly :\n546:/-! ## Part 5: Running Parity is Not Linearly Computable -/\n548:/-- Running parity function: parity(x_1,...,x_t) at each position t -/\n549:noncomputable def runningParity (T : ℕ) : (Fin T → ℝ) → (Fin T → ℝ) :=\n554:/-- Running parity extends XOR: it requires computing XOR at each position.\n557:theorem running_parity_not_linear (T : ℕ) (hT : T ≥ 2) :\n717:/-- E88 can compute running parity by maintaining a sign-flip state.\n720:theorem e88_computes_running_parity (T : ℕ) (_hT : 0 < T) :\n729:/-! ## Part 6: XOR Chain Separation -/\n731:/-- XOR chain: y_t = x_1 XOR x_2 XOR ... XOR x_t -/\n732:noncomputable def xorChain (T : ℕ) : (Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) → (Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) :=\n738:/-- XOR chain cannot be computed by D-layer linear-temporal models for T > 2^D.\n741:theorem xor_chain_not_multilayer_linear (D : ℕ) (T : ℕ) (hT : T > 2^D) :\n765:/-- E88 (single layer with temporal tanh) can compute XOR chain.\n768:theorem e88_computes_xor_chain (T : ℕ) :\n832:/-! ## Part 7: Head Independence in E88 -/\n834:/-- E88 multi-head state: each head has independent state S^h -/\n839:/-- E88 head update is independent: each head's next state depends only on\n841:noncomputable def e88HeadUpdate (α : ℝ) (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ)\n845:theorem e88_heads_independent (H d : ℕ) (α : ℝ)\n852:/-- Each E88 head runs its own independent temporal dynamics.\n854:theorem e88_head_independence (H d : ℕ) :\n864:/-! ## Part 8: Alert State Persistence -/\n866:/-- An \"alert\" state is one where |S| > θ for some threshold θ.\n868:def isAlertState (S : ℝ) (θ : ℝ) : Prop := |S| > θ\n870:/-- Alert state basin: the set of states that will evolve to stay alert. -/","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"23a5d44b-efaf-4468-b1ae-0b067e647cf0","uuid":"92a10ccd-5017-48c7-bfd8-87bde8667265","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"1:/-\n22:/-!\n67:/-! ## Part 1: Tanh Saturation Properties -/\n69:/-- Tanh approaches ±1 as input magnitude grows. Already proven as tendsto_tanh_atTop. -/\n70:theorem tanh_saturates_to_one : Filter.Tendsto tanh Filter.atTop (nhds 1) :=\n73:/-- Tanh approaches -1 as input approaches -∞. -/\n74:theorem tanh_saturates_to_neg_one : Filter.Tendsto tanh Filter.atBot (nhds (-1)) := by\n85:/-- The derivative of tanh vanishes as |x| → ∞. This is the key saturation property.\n87:theorem tanh_derivative_vanishes (ε : ℝ) (hε : 0 < ε) :\n91:/-! ## Part 2: Fixed Point Analysis for Tanh Recurrence -/\n93:/-- A simple tanh recurrence: S_{t+1} = tanh(α·S_t + b) -/\n94:noncomputable def tanhRecurrence (α b : ℝ) (S : ℝ) : ℝ := tanh (α * S + b)\n96:/-- When |α| < 1, the tanh recurrence is a contraction on [-1, 1].\n98:theorem tanhRecurrence_is_contraction (α : ℝ) (_hα : |α| < 1) (b : ℝ) :\n114:/-- For |α| < 1, the tanh recurrence has a unique fixed point. -/\n115:theorem tanhRecurrence_unique_fixedpoint (α : ℝ) (hα_lt : |α| < 1) (_hα_pos : 0 < |α|) (b : ℝ) :\n158:/-- Near saturation (|S| close to 1), the state becomes \"latched\" because\n160:theorem near_saturation_low_gradient (α : ℝ) (_hα : |α| ≤ 1) (b S : ℝ)\n188:/-! ## Part 3: Binary Retention - Latching vs Decay -/\n190:/-- E88-style state update with tanh nonlinearity.\n192:noncomputable def e88StateUpdate (α : ℝ) (S k : ℝ) (δ : ℝ) : ℝ := tanh (α * S + δ * k)\n194:/-- Linear state update (Mamba2-style): S_{t+1} = α·S_t + B·x_t -/\n195:noncomputable def linearStateUpdate (α : ℝ) (S x : ℝ) (B : ℝ) : ℝ := α * S + B * x\n197:/-- A latched state in E88: once |S| is close to 1, it stays close to 1.\n204:theorem e88_latched_state_persists (α : ℝ) (hα : 0 < α) (hα_lt : α < 2) (hα_large : α > 9/10)\n337:/-- Linear state decays exponentially when |α| < 1 (stable case). -/\n338:theorem linear_state_decay (α : ℝ) (hα : |α| < 1) (S₀ : ℝ) :\n358:/-- The key difference: E88 can maintain a nonzero state indefinitely,\n360:theorem latching_vs_decay :\n411:/-! ## Part 4: Exact Counting with Tanh -/\n413:/-- A counting state: tracks count mod n using saturating dynamics.\n421:/-- E88 can implement a counter mod n for small n by using multiple heads\n424:theorem e88_can_count_mod (n : ℕ) (hn : 0 < n) :\n489:/-- Linear systems cannot count: they can only track weighted sums.\n498:theorem linear_cannot_count_exactly :\n546:/-! ## Part 5: Running Parity is Not Linearly Computable -/\n548:/-- Running parity function: parity(x_1,...,x_t) at each position t -/\n549:noncomputable def runningParity (T : ℕ) : (Fin T → ℝ) → (Fin T → ℝ) :=\n554:/-- Running parity extends XOR: it requires computing XOR at each position.\n557:theorem running_parity_not_linear (T : ℕ) (hT : T ≥ 2) :\n717:/-- E88 can compute running parity by maintaining a sign-flip state.\n720:theorem e88_computes_running_parity (T : ℕ) (_hT : 0 < T) :\n729:/-! ## Part 6: XOR Chain Separation -/\n731:/-- XOR chain: y_t = x_1 XOR x_2 XOR ... XOR x_t -/\n732:noncomputable def xorChain (T : ℕ) : (Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) → (Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) :=\n738:/-- XOR chain cannot be computed by D-layer linear-temporal models for T > 2^D.\n741:theorem xor_chain_not_multilayer_linear (D : ℕ) (T : ℕ) (hT : T > 2^D) :\n765:/-- E88 (single layer with temporal tanh) can compute XOR chain.\n768:theorem e88_computes_xor_chain (T : ℕ) :\n832:/-! ## Part 7: Head Independence in E88 -/\n834:/-- E88 multi-head state: each head has independent state S^h -/\n839:/-- E88 head update is independent: each head's next state depends only on\n841:noncomputable def e88HeadUpdate (α : ℝ) (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ)\n845:theorem e88_heads_independent (H d : ℕ) (α : ℝ)\n852:/-- Each E88 head runs its own independent temporal dynamics.\n854:theorem e88_head_independence (H d : ℕ) :\n864:/-! ## Part 8: Alert State Persistence -/\n866:/-- An \"alert\" state is one where |S| > θ for some threshold θ.\n868:def isAlertState (S : ℝ) (θ : ℝ) : Prop := |S| > θ\n870:/-- Alert state basin: the set of states that will evolve to stay alert. -/","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Mv2AujemuZBdCNGcji6HKj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clearer picture. Let me check the TanhSaturation.lean theorem at line 338 and understand the references better:\n\n1. LinearCapacity.lean:72 - document says \"In any linear recurrence with contraction factor |alpha| < 1, state decays exponentially: |h_T| = O(alpha^T |h_0|)\". The theorem at line 72 is `linear_state_is_sum` which is about state being a sum of inputs. The actual exponential decay theorem is `linear_state_decay` at line 338 in TanhSaturation.lean! But the document references LinearCapacity.lean:72. This seems wrong.\n\n\nLooking at the grep output, LinearCapacity.lean doesn't actually contain an exponential decay theorem—it has `linear_state_is_sum`, `state_additive`, `state_scalar`, and similar results. The exponential decay theorem is clearly in TanhSaturation.lean, so either the reference is pointing to the wrong file, or the document text about exponential decay is being quoted from a different context that I need to trace more carefully. I'm checking whether `linear_state_is_sum` at LinearCapacity.lean:72 is the right reference for the exponential decay claim, since that theorem describes state structure rather than decay itself—the actual decay result is `linear_state_decay` in TanhSaturation.lean:338. The doc's point about distant inputs being attenuated fits better with the decay theorem, though `linear_state_is_sum` does show how past inputs contribute to current state through the weighted sum structure.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2994,"cache_read_input_tokens":38254,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2994},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,