{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YXZoJzkWKb2XyJJ6NSnEqs","type":"tool_result","content":"   380→/-! ## Part 7: Head Independence -/\n   381→\n   382→/-- **PROPERTY 5: E88 Heads Evolve Independently**\n   383→\n   384→Each head's state update depends only on:\n   385→1. Its own previous state S^h_{t-1}\n   386→2. The current input x_t (through its own K_h, V_h projections)\n   387→\n   388→There is NO cross-head communication in the state dynamics. -/\n   389→theorem e88_heads_independent (model : E88Model h d d) (T : ℕ)\n   390→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (h1 h2 : Fin h) :\n   391→    -- Head h1's final state is independent of head h2's parameters\n   392→    let state := e88MultiHeadState model T inputs 0\n   393→    -- Changing head h2's parameters doesn't affect head h1's state\n   394→    ∀ (head2' : E88Head d d),\n   395→      let model' : E88Model h d d := { model with\n   396→        heads := fun i => if i = h2 then head2' else model.heads i }\n   397→      let state' := e88MultiHeadState model' T inputs 0\n   398→      h1 ≠ h2 → state h1 = state' h1 := by\n   399→  intro state head2' model' state' h_neq\n   400→  simp only [e88MultiHeadState, e88HeadStateAfterT]\n   401→  -- The key observation: e88HeadStateAfterT for head h1 only uses model.heads h1\n   402→  -- Since model'.heads h1 = model.heads h1 (because h1 ≠ h2), the states are equal\n   403→  have h_heads_eq : model'.heads h1 = model.heads h1 := by\n   404→    simp only [model']\n   405→    split_ifs with h_eq\n   406→    · exact absurd h_eq h_neq\n   407→    · rfl\n   408→  -- Since the head parameters are the same and inputs are the same, states are equal\n   409→  rw [h_heads_eq]\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"23a5d44b-efaf-4468-b1ae-0b067e647cf0","uuid":"7a68b9f4-9b93-491b-8e96-ed9d287b7b1a","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E88Definition.lean","content":"/-! ## Part 7: Head Independence -/\n\n/-- **PROPERTY 5: E88 Heads Evolve Independently**\n\nEach head's state update depends only on:\n1. Its own previous state S^h_{t-1}\n2. The current input x_t (through its own K_h, V_h projections)\n\nThere is NO cross-head communication in the state dynamics. -/\ntheorem e88_heads_independent (model : E88Model h d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (h1 h2 : Fin h) :\n    -- Head h1's final state is independent of head h2's parameters\n    let state := e88MultiHeadState model T inputs 0\n    -- Changing head h2's parameters doesn't affect head h1's state\n    ∀ (head2' : E88Head d d),\n      let model' : E88Model h d d := { model with\n        heads := fun i => if i = h2 then head2' else model.heads i }\n      let state' := e88MultiHeadState model' T inputs 0\n      h1 ≠ h2 → state h1 = state' h1 := by\n  intro state head2' model' state' h_neq\n  simp only [e88MultiHeadState, e88HeadStateAfterT]\n  -- The key observation: e88HeadStateAfterT for head h1 only uses model.heads h1\n  -- Since model'.heads h1 = model.heads h1 (because h1 ≠ h2), the states are equal\n  have h_heads_eq : model'.heads h1 = model.heads h1 := by\n    simp only [model']\n    split_ifs with h_eq\n    · exact absurd h_eq h_neq\n    · rfl\n  -- Since the head parameters are the same and inputs are the same, states are equal\n  rw [h_heads_eq]","numLines":30,"startLine":380,"totalLines":651}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012tPhHiYEFASKvDExRpVWpZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Great progress. Now let me check E88Definition.lean:433 and ExpressivityHierarchy.lean:267.\n\nAlso, let me now look for the \"Soft Threshold\" theorem in TanhSaturation.lean - the doc says it computes soft threshold, meaning \"accumulated positive signal drives S toward +1\". The `e88_can_count_mod` at TanhSaturation.lean:424 is about counting mod n, which is not quite \"soft threshold detection\". \n\nLet me look for better options. Looking at TanhSaturation:\n- Line 557: running_parity_not_linear \n\n\n- Line 498: linear_cannot_count_exactly\n\nI'm noticing the document structure maps theorems across files - \"E88 Computes Soft Threshold\" and \"E88 Counts Modulo n\" both point to essentially the same counting mod n result, just in different locations.\n\nThe soft threshold behavior seems to be about saturation - when accumulated positive signals push the value toward +1 through tanh. The most relevant theorems appear to be either `e88_can_count_mod` for the modular counting aspect or `e88_latched_state_persists` for the saturation persistence, though I need to check what the document actually claims about soft threshold computation.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2296,"cache_read_input_tokens":59814,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2296},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"23a5d44b-efaf-4468-b1ae-0b067e647cf0","uuid":"bace325d-a984-48bd-bdbe-0f853cd8bfb7"}
